</p></sec><sec id="Sec8"><title>Female and male students&#x02019; career preferences</title><p>Table&#x000a0;<xref rid="Tab2" ref-type="table">2</xref> shows the levels of interest for specialty choices as a career by female and male students. The most common specialties chosen by the students were general medicine/family medicine (18.8&#x000a0;%), surgery (9.5&#x000a0;%), pediatrics (7.6&#x000a0;%), special Internal medicine (7.1&#x000a0;%), emergency medicine (4.6&#x000a0;%), orthopedics (3.8&#x000a0;%), and urology (3.3&#x000a0;%). The other specialties chosen are listed in Table&#x000a0;<xref rid="Tab2" ref-type="table">2</xref>. Women significantly preferred pediatrics, obstetrics &#x00026; gynecology, and psychology than men. Men significantly preferred surgery and orthopedics than women.<table-wrap id="Tab2"><label>Table 2</label><caption><p>Female and male students&#x02019; career preferences</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th/><th/><th>Total</th><th>Women</th><th>Men</th><th rowspan="2">
